{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_1","type":"agent_message","text":"**Topology Summary**\n\nUse a 5 V single-supply behavioral op-amp RC phase-shift oscillator. The output node must be exactly `Vout`. The oscillator core is a high-gain inverting amplifier centered at `Vcm = 2.5 V`, with a three-section RC phase-shift ladder feeding `Vout` back to the inverting input `Vinn`. The non-inverting input `Vinp` is fixed at `Vcm`.\n\nThe design should have startup loop gain comfortably above unity. Since the three-section RC ladder attenuates by about 1/29 at oscillation, the inverting gain stage should target about 35 to 50 small-signal gain, then rely on supply-limited behavioral output or soft limiting to stabilize amplitude.\n\n**Device/Function List**\n\n- `VDD` supply: independent 5 V DC source from `VDD` to `0`.\n- Mid-supply divider:\n  - Equal resistors from `VDD` to `Vcm` and `Vcm` to `0`.\n  - Bypass capacitor from `Vcm` to `0`.\n- Behavioral op-amp-like gain block:\n  - Explicit input nodes `Vinp` and `Vinn`.\n  - `Vinp` tied to `Vcm`.\n  - Output exactly `Vout`.\n  - Output limited between 0 V and 5 V, preferably with smooth limiting around rails.\n- Three RC phase-shift sections:\n  - Use equal values, for example `R = 10k`, `C = 10nF`.\n  - Intermediate nodes such as `n1`, `n2`, `n3`.\n  - Final ladder node should drive `Vinn`.\n- Bias resistor:\n  - Large resistor from `Vinn` or `n3` to `Vcm`, for example 1 MOhm to 10 MOhm, to define DC without strongly loading the ladder.\n- Gain-setting network:\n  - Inverting gain equivalent around 35 to 50.\n  - Avoid using values that significantly load the RC ladder.\n\n**Bias/Reference Strategy**\n\nAll oscillator signal nodes should be DC-referenced to `Vcm`, not ground. The RC ladder resistors should return to `Vcm` so the AC phase shift occurs around the 2.5 V common-mode level. `Vinp` should be directly biased to `Vcm`.\n\nUse startup asymmetry with `.ic`, for example slight mismatch between `Vinp` and `Vinn`, or initial ladder-node voltages such as `n1`, `n2`, `n3` slightly offset from 2.5 V. Do not rely only on numerical noise.\n\n**Signal Or Feedback Path**\n\nThe intended loop is:\n\n`Vout -> RC ladder section 1 -> n1 -> RC ladder section 2 -> n2 -> RC ladder section 3 -> n3/Vinn -> high-gain inverting amplifier -> Vout`\n\nThe RC ladder supplies about 180 degrees phase shift near the oscillation frequency. The inverting amplifier supplies the additional 180 degrees. For `R = 10k` and `C = 10nF`, expect a visible low-kHz or sub-kHz oscillation, roughly 600 Hz to 1 kHz depending on loading.\n\n**SPICE/Netlist Constraints**\n\n- Final output node name must be exactly `Vout`.\n- Include exactly `.tran 1u 5m`.\n- No external input source is needed.\n- Do not leave `Vinn`, `Vinp`, `n1`, `n2`, `n3`, `Vcm`, or `Vout` floating.\n- Behavioral amplifier output must be rail-compatible with 0 V to 5 V.\n- Keep DC operating point near `Vcm`.\n- Use `.ic` or startup-compatible initial capacitor conditions.\n\n**Failure Risks To Avoid**\n\n- Gain too low: previous failure showed only about 20 mV output amplitude, so use gain above 29, preferably 35 to 50.\n- Ladder referenced to ground instead of `Vcm`, which breaks single-supply operation.\n- Excessively loading the RC ladder with small gain-setting or bias resistors.\n- Hard saturation at 0 V or 5 V without recovery; use smooth limiting or enough feedback biasing so `Vout` swings around `Vcm`.\n- Floating final ladder node or undefined `Vinn` DC point.\n- Over-damped startup from no initial mismatch or too much shunt loading.\n- Incorrect output node name; the checker requires `Vout`."}}
